Creating a function that converts Markdown formatted text to HTML formatted text can be quite complex, as it involves parsing the Markdown syntax and converting it to the corresponding HTML elements. Below is a simplified example of how you might approach this task. This function is not complete and does not cover all Markdown syntax, but it should give you an idea of how to start.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <map>

// A simple map to convert some Markdown to HTML
std::map<char, std::string> markdownToHtmlMap = {
    {'*', "*"},
    {'[', "["},
    {'(', "("},
    {']', "]"},
    {')', ")"},
    {'#', "#"},
    {'`', "`"},
    {'&', "&"},
    {'<', "<"},
    {'>', ">"},
    {' ', " "}
};

// A function to convert a single character from Markdown to HTML
std::string convertChar(char c) {
    if (markdownToHtmlMap.find(c) != markdownToHtmlMap.end()) {
        return markdownToHtmlMap[c];
    }
    return std::string(1, c);
}

// A function to convert a Markdown-formatted string to an HTML-formatted string
std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    for (const auto& c : markdown) {
        html += convertChar(c);
    }
    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "Hello *world*!";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << "Markdown: " << markdown << std::endl;
    std::cout << "HTML: " << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This code defines a map from Markdown characters to their HTML equivalents. It then provides a function `convertChar` that converts a single character from Markdown to HTML. Finally, `markdownToHtml` iterates over each character in the Markdown string and applies the conversion.

Please note that this is a very basic example and does not cover many Markdown features such as headers, lists, blockquotes, and code blocks. Implementing a full Markdown to HTML converter would require a more sophisticated parsing approach and a deeper understanding of both Markdown and HTML syntax.

For a more comprehensive solution, you might want to look into existing Markdown parsing libraries for C++, such as [POCO Markdown](https://pocoproject.org/docs/Poco.Markup.MarkdownParser.html) or [CppMark](https://github.com/cppmark/cppmark), which can handle a wide range of Markdown syntax and produce a well-formed HTML output.

