Here's a function in JavaScript that takes an array of 5 numbers as input and checks if any of the numbers is a prime number. If a number is found to be prime, it will be printed to the console.

```javascript
function checkForPrimes(numbers) {
  // Check if each number in the array is a prime number
  for (let i = 0; i < numbers.length; i++) {
    let number = numbers[i];
    if (isPrime(number)) {
      console.log(`Number ${number} is a prime number.`);
      return; // Exit the function after finding and printing a prime number
    }
  }

  // If no prime number is found, print a message
  console.log("No prime numbers found in the array.");
}

// Function to check if a number is prime
function isPrime(number) {
  // A number is prime if it's greater than 1 and has no positive divisors other than 1 and itself
  if (number <= 1) {
    return false;
  }
  for (let i = 2; i < number; i++) {
    if (number % i === 0) {
      return false;
    }
  }
  return true;
}

// Example usage
const numbers = [10, 12, 15, 17, 20];
checkForPrimes(numbers);
```

This function will output something like:

```
Number 17 is a prime number.
```

If none of the numbers in the array are prime, it will output:

```
No prime numbers found in the array.
```

Please note that this function uses a naive approach to check if a number is prime, which is not the most efficient way to do so. For large numbers, a more sophisticated algorithm like the Miller-Rabin primality test or the AKS primality test should be used. However, for small numbers up to a few hundred, this simple method is sufficient.

